## GUARDRAILS — ENFORCED IN CODE, NOT JUST PROMPTS

### System Prompt Level (soft guardrails)
- Encoded in the system prompts under prompts/ directory
- Different per conversation mode (provider, family, outbound)
- Includes explicit instructions: "Never give medical advice", "Never confirm admission without eligibility check"

### Code Level (hard guardrails — GuardrailService)
The GuardrailService runs on EVERY outgoing message before it's sent to Twilio:

```python
BLOCKED_PATTERNS = [
    r'\b(SSN|social security)\b.*\d{3}-?\d{2}-?\d{4}',  # Full SSN
    r'\byou (should|must|need to) take\b',                # Medical advice
    r'\byou are (admitted|accepted|approved)\b',           # Premature admission confirmation
    r'\bguarantee\b',                                       # Guarantee language
    r'\byour nurse will be\b',                              # Specific caregiver promise
    r'\byour first visit is on\b',                          # Specific date promise
]
```

If any pattern matches, the message is blocked and rewritten with a safe alternative.

### Confidence Threshold Level
- Eligibility result confidence < 0.7 → Voice Agent says "I'll need to have our coordinator verify..." NOT "we can accept"
- Extracted field confidence < 0.5 → goes to gap list, Voice Agent asks caller to confirm
- Never auto-populate a field with confidence < 0.3

### Escalation Triggers
- Caller asks to speak to a human → ConversationRelay `end` session with handoff data
- Caller is angry or distressed → acknowledge, offer human coordinator
- 3+ failed attempts to understand caller → "Let me connect you with our coordinator"
- Clinical question beyond intake scope → redirect to coordinator
- Maximum call duration exceeded (15 minutes) → wrap up, schedule follow-up

